SIMPLE: double-decker
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Double-decker
<hw>Dou"ble-deck"er</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn>
<fld>(Naut.)</fld> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A man-of-war having two gun
decks.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>A tenement house having two families on
each floor.</def> <mark>[Local, U. S.]</mark> <sd>(b)</sd> <def>A
biplane a⟦eum⟧roplane or kite.</def> <mark>[Colloq.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>anything having two decks or levels, as a bus with
two levels for passengers. In older vehicles, less often today, the
upper deck was open, as on street cars.</def> <mark>[Colloq.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Double-dye</ent>⟦br⟧
